;; Backus, The Acoustical Foundations of Music (Norton, 1969) for the physics summary.

(chapter
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 14
  :title \"Pitch, Interval, and the Harmonic Series\"
  :short-title \"pitch-interval-harmonic-series\"
  :estimated-words 3500
  :philosopher-weave (peirce wittgenstein-late aristotle)

  :prose
\"Everything we have talked about so far — melody, harmony, form, phrasing, rubato — sits on top of a single physical fact. When a string on a piano is struck or a column of air in a flute is set vibrating, it moves back and forth many times per second. The number of times per second is called the *frequency*. Our ears convert frequency into what we hear as *pitch*: high frequencies sound high; low frequencies sound low. That's the whole basis.

But it turns out that a vibrating string doesn't just vibrate at one frequency. It vibrates at many, all at once. The physical fact underneath this is that a string tied at both ends can vibrate in halves, in thirds, in quarters, in fifths — dividing itself up into shorter and shorter sub-vibrations, each faster than the last. All these sub-vibrations happen simultaneously, layered over each other. Together they form what is called the **harmonic series**, or the **overtone series**. This chapter is about what that means, why it produces the musical intervals we call consonant, and how the whole apparatus of Western music (and much non-Western music) is built on top of the harmonic series without most listeners ever knowing.

# Pitch as frequency

A pitch is a frequency. When we say the note A above middle C on a piano is 'A440,' we mean the piano is tuned so that when you strike that key, the string vibrates at 440 cycles per second — 440 Hertz.

The relationship between frequency and pitch is *logarithmic*, not linear. If you double the frequency of a note, you get a note one octave higher. A440 doubled is A880 — the A one octave above. Double A880 and you get A1760 — two octaves above. This is not a linear step; it's a doubling. Every octave doubles the frequency.

Why octaves? Why does doubling the frequency produce a note that our ears hear as *the same note*, just higher? Because when a string vibrates at 880 Hz, its vibration pattern is exactly a version of the 440 Hz pattern, just twice as fast. The 880 Hz wave completes two full cycles in the time the 440 Hz wave completes one. Every peak of the 880 Hz wave aligns with either a peak of the 440 Hz wave or the midpoint between two of its peaks. The two waves fit together *perfectly*. When we hear them at the same time, we do not hear two different pitches; we hear one pitch with a slightly richer quality. The ear categorizes them as the same note.

This is the first miracle. Doubled frequencies sound like the same note.

# The harmonic series

Now the second miracle. When you strike a string on a piano, the string does not vibrate only at its fundamental frequency (say A110, if it's the A two octaves below the tuning A). It vibrates at A110 *and* at 220 Hz (one octave up) *and* at 330 Hz *and* at 440 Hz *and* at 550 Hz *and* on, and on, in a series of integer multiples of the fundamental.

Written out for a fundamental of A110:

1st harmonic (the fundamental): 110 Hz — A
2nd harmonic: 220 Hz — A (one octave up)
3rd harmonic: 330 Hz — E (a fifth above the octave A)
4th harmonic: 440 Hz — A (two octaves up)
5th harmonic: 550 Hz — C-sharp (a major third above the double-octave A)
6th harmonic: 660 Hz — E (a fifth above the double-octave A)
7th harmonic: 770 Hz — approximately G (slightly flat of the equal-tempered G)
8th harmonic: 880 Hz — A (three octaves up)

The intervals between successive harmonics get smaller as we go up. Between the 1st and 2nd is an octave. Between the 2nd and 3rd is a perfect fifth. Between the 3rd and 4th is a perfect fourth. Between the 4th and 5th is a major third. Between the 5th and 6th is a minor third. And on it goes.

These intervals — the octave, the fifth, the fourth, the major third — are exactly the intervals Western music calls *consonant*. They are the intervals that form the bones of every triad, every chord, every cadence in tonal music. They are called consonant because when two notes at these frequency ratios are played together, their harmonic series line up cleanly and the sound feels stable to the ear.

This is not a cultural invention. It is a fact about how sound waves behave. Music theorists across many cultures — Chinese, Indian, Greek, Arab — independently arrived at scale systems built around octaves, fifths, and fourths, because those intervals are baked into the physics of vibrating strings and air columns. Cultures differ in *which* consonant intervals they emphasize, and in how they subdivide the space between them, but the basic set is a physical universal.

# Intervals in Western music

An **interval** in Western music theory is a distance between two pitches, named by counting steps in the diatonic scale. From C up to G is a fifth (C, D, E, F, G — five step-names). From C up to E is a third. From C up to F is a fourth. The interval names count the letter-names, including both endpoints.

Some intervals have *quality* attached: major, minor, perfect, augmented, diminished. A major third is four semitones (C to E). A minor third is three semitones (C to E-flat). A perfect fifth is seven semitones (C to G). A tritone (also called an augmented fourth or diminished fifth) is six semitones (C to F-sharp), and this interval is famously unstable — the ear does not know where to put it and expects it to resolve.

In modern Western tuning, called **equal temperament**, the octave is divided into twelve equal semitones. Each semitone is the same ratio as the next: the twelfth root of two, roughly 1.0595. This means the interval from C to C-sharp is the same size (as a frequency ratio) as the interval from D to D-sharp, or F to F-sharp. It is a *tempered* system: the intervals are slightly out of tune compared to the pure harmonic-series ratios (a pure perfect fifth is a 3:2 ratio; equal temperament's fifth is 2^(7/12), which is a hair narrower than 3:2), but the small compromise means every key on the piano sounds equally good, and modulation between keys is smooth.

Equal temperament is a modern compromise. Before it became standard in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, keyboards were tuned in various ways (Pythagorean, meantone, well-tempered) that made some keys sound more in-tune and others sound worse. Bach's *Well-Tempered Clavier* (Book 1 published 1722, Book 2 in 1742) was written in part to demonstrate that a properly tempered tuning could handle *all* twenty-four major and minor keys. Today, when a pianist plays Bach, they are almost certainly using equal temperament — technically a small betrayal of Bach's intent, but the compromise nobody has quite been willing to undo.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's write a small program that generates the harmonic series from a fundamental.

```scheme
;; Generate the first n harmonics of a fundamental frequency.
;; Each harmonic is an integer multiple of the fundamental.

(define (harmonic-series fundamental-hz n)
  (map (lambda (i) (* fundamental-hz i))
       (range 1 (+ n 1))))

;; For A110 (the A two octaves below the tuning A):
(harmonic-series 110 8)
; => (110 220 330 440 550 660 770 880)

;; Convert a frequency to the nearest pitch name, given equal temperament
;; where A4 = 440 Hz. Uses log base 2.
(define (freq->pitch hz)
  (let* ((semitones-from-a4 (* 12 (log (/ hz 440) 2)))
         (rounded (round semitones-from-a4))
         (pitches #(C C# D D# E F F# G G# A A# B))
         (pitch-index (modulo (+ rounded 9) 12))     ; A is index 9
         (octave (+ 4 (quotient (+ rounded 9) 12))))
    (list (vector-ref pitches pitch-index) octave (- semitones-from-a4 rounded))))

(freq->pitch 110)   ; => (A 2 0)          — exactly A2
(freq->pitch 330)   ; => (E 4 0.0196)     — nearly E4, slightly sharp
(freq->pitch 550)   ; => (C# 5 -0.137)    — nearly C#5, noticeably flat
(freq->pitch 770)   ; => (G 5 -0.313)     — noticeably flat of G5
```

The last few outputs are worth thinking about. The 3rd harmonic (330 Hz over a 110 Hz fundamental) is *slightly sharp* of the equal-tempered E — by about two cents (a cent is 1/100 of a semitone). The 5th harmonic (C-sharp) is *fourteen cents flat* of the equal-tempered C-sharp — a difference the ear can hear. The 7th harmonic (G) is *thirty cents flat* of the equal-tempered G — a difference that in a solo instrument would sound conspicuously out of tune.

This is the price of equal temperament. The pure ratios of the harmonic series are not exactly what a piano gives you. When a violinist or a singer performs alone or in a small ensemble, they will often adjust their tuning to match the pure ratios — the violinist plays a fifth slightly wider, the singer sings a third slightly narrower — because the pure intervals sound better when the notes stand exposed. When they play with a piano, they compromise back to the tempered intervals because that's what the piano has.

# Why this matters for how music sounds

The harmonic series is why:

Two notes an octave apart sound like the same note. Their harmonics almost completely align.

A fifth (C and G together) sounds stable. The 3rd harmonic of C is a G; the 2nd harmonic of G is a G; they reinforce each other.

A major triad (C, E, G) sounds resolved. C's harmonics contain both G and E (the 5th harmonic); E's harmonics reinforce the E; G's harmonics reinforce the G. The three notes overlap in ways that make the ear register them as *one thing*.

A minor triad (C, E-flat, G) is slightly less consonant than a major triad. The E-flat is not in C's natural harmonic series (which contains E, not E-flat), so the minor third sits on top of the C somewhat as a color rather than as a reinforcement. This is one reason (there are others) that minor sounds sadder than major to a Western-trained ear: it is very slightly acoustically unresolved.

A tritone (C and F-sharp) sounds unstable. The F-sharp is not in C's harmonic series at all, in any low-numbered position. The ear has no natural place to put the interval, and it feels the need to resolve.

This is the physical substrate of what music theory calls consonance and dissonance. The theory names the qualities; the physics explains them.

# What the listener hears versus what the score says

There is a gap between what is written in a score and what a listener hears. A composer writes 'E' and 'G' on a staff, and a piano plays two tempered pitches close to (but slightly off from) the pure E and G. The listener hears the two pitches interact — hears their overtones layer, their beats resolve into resonance, their combined sound thicken into a chord. What is on the page is symbolic; what is in the ear is acoustic.

Great composers know this gap. They write in the language of the score but they compose *for the ear* — for what the piano's tempered tuning will actually produce when the ideas are played. Some composers (Debussy, for example, in *La Cathédrale engloutie*, 1910) exploit the gap by writing chords whose beauty depends on the way tempered piano tones layer — chords that would sound different on a differently tuned instrument. Some composers (Harry Partch in the twentieth century, La Monte Young later) rebelled against equal temperament entirely and built new instruments tuned in pure ratios, discovering intervals we don't have letter-names for.

Most of us listen to music played in equal temperament on modern instruments. We don't notice the compromise because our ears have grown up inside it. But knowing the compromise is there — knowing that the pure harmonic series and the tempered piano are two different objects — makes a listener more curious about *what* they are hearing when a chord lands and *why* one voicing of a chord sounds different from another.

# Tie back

This chapter has been the physics under everything else. Pitch is frequency. Frequencies double at the octave. When a string vibrates, it vibrates in the harmonic series — integer multiples of a fundamental — and that series contains all the intervals Western music calls consonant. Modern pianos are tuned in equal temperament, which is a small compromise that lets every key sound equally good and lets modulation between keys be smooth.

If you understand this — really understand it — you will hear music differently. You will notice how a plain fifth sounds stable and a plain seventh sounds like it wants to move. You will hear the harmonic ring of a low piano note as its overtones stack up. You will hear the tuning of a solo violinist bend the equal-tempered pitches back toward the pure ratios in an exposed passage. Music becomes a physical object rather than a set of instructions.

Next chapter: tempo, rubato, and listening — how *time* is treated in performance, what it means to play 'in time' and 'out of time,' and why the same piece played by two great pianists can sound like two different pieces.

# Sources cited in this chapter

Hermann Helmholtz, *On the Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music* (1863, English translation by Alexander J. Ellis, 1875). The founding modern text on musical acoustics, in the public domain.

John Backus, *The Acoustical Foundations of Music* (New York: Norton, 1969). A twentieth-century standard reference.

Grove Music Online, entries 'Pitch' (article by Ellen Rosand and others), 'Interval' (article by Ian Bent and others), and 'Overtone series' (article by Peter A. Bloom).

For temperament history: Ross W. Duffin, *How Equal Temperament Ruined Harmony (and Why You Should Care)* (Norton, 2007) — a partisan but useful survey.\"

  :notes
\"All physical claims are standard and verifiable. Frequency ratios: octave = 2:1, perfect fifth = 3:2 (pure), 2^(7/12) ≈ 1.4983 (tempered — very close). Major third (5:4 pure) vs tempered (2^(4/12) ≈ 1.2599) differs by about 14 cents. Seventh harmonic vs tempered minor seventh differs by about 31 cents flat. These numbers are checkable. The Bach Well-Tempered Clavier dates (1722, 1742) are the standard scholarly dates.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Peirce: the harmonic series as index — the physical vibration causally connects the ear to the frequency. A pitch is a real object in the world.
Wittgenstein-late: consonance as a form-of-life recognition — cultures share the harmonic series but name and use it differently. We agree that a fifth is 'stable' because our ears grew up in shared acoustic worlds.
Aristotle: the harmonic series as the natural material out of which musical forms are made — the substance underneath every accident.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Chapter 15 will look at tempo and rubato — how time itself is shaped in performance, and how listening changes when you know how to listen for what a performer is doing with time.\")
")
